      <!-- Reference & Constants -->
      <div class="chapter" id="constants">
        <h2>Reference & Constants</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Quick Reference</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Avogadro’s Number:</b> <code>6.022 × 10²³</code> particles/mol</li>
            <li><b>Gas Constant (R):</b> <code>0.0821</code> L·atm/(mol·K)</li>
            <li><b>STP:</b> 0°C (273K), 1 atm, 1 mol gas = 22.4 L</li>
            <li><b>Density:</b> <code>d = m/V</code></li>
            <li><b>Faraday’s Constant:</b> 96,485 C/mol e⁻</li>
            <li><b>pH:</b> <code>pH = –log[H⁺]</code></li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Nomenclature & Polyatomics -->
      <div class="chapter" id="nomenclature">
        <h2>Nomenclature & Polyatomic Ions</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Key Rules & Examples</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Ionic compounds:</b> Metal + nonmetal, e.g., <code>NaCl</code> = Sodium chloride</li>
            <li><b>Covalent compounds:</b> Use prefixes, e.g., <code>CO₂</code> = Carbon dioxide</li>
            <li><b>Common Polyatomic Ions:</b>
              <ul>
                <li><code>NO₃⁻</code> Nitrate, <code>SO₄²⁻</code> Sulfate, <code>NH₄⁺</code> Ammonium, <code>CO₃²⁻</code> Carbonate</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
          <b>Challenge Q:</b> What is the name of <code>Fe(NO₃)₂</code>? <b>A:</b> Iron(II) nitrate
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Bonding & Structures -->
      <div class="chapter" id="bonding">
        <h2>Bonding & Structures</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Summary & Examples</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Ionic Bond:</b> Transfer of electrons (NaCl)</li>
            <li><b>Covalent Bond:</b> Sharing electrons (H₂O)</li>
            <li><b>Lewis Structure Example (NO₃⁻):</b> N central, 3 O, one double bond, resonance</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Q:</b> Draw the Lewis structure for <code>CO₃²⁻</code>.  
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Solutions & Molarity -->
      <div class="chapter" id="solutions">
        <h2>Solutions & Molarity</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Formulas & Problems</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Molarity:</b> <code>M = mol/L</code></li>
            <li><b>Molality:</b> <code>m = mol/kg</code></li>
            <li><b>Dilution:</b> <code>M₁V₁ = M₂V₂</code></li>
            <li><b>Percent by mass:</b> <code>(g solute/g solution) × 100</code></li>
          </ul>
          <b>Challenge:</b> How many mL of 6M HCl to make 250 mL of 1M HCl? <br>
          <b>Solution:</b> <code>V₁ = (1)(0.25)/(6) = 0.0417 L = 41.7 mL</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Empirical/Molecular Formula -->
      <div class="chapter" id="formulas">
        <h2>Empirical/Molecular Formula</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Review & Problems</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Empirical Formula:</b> Simplest whole number ratio</li>
            <li><b>Molecular Formula:</b> (Empirical) × n</li>
            <li><b>Ex:</b> 40% C, 6.7% H, 53.3% O ⇒ CH₂O</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Practice:</b> What is the empirical formula if 29% Na, 40.6% S, 30.4% O?  
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Gas Laws & Molar Volume -->
      <div class="chapter" id="gases">
        <h2>Gas Laws & Molar Volume</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Quick Sheet</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Boyle’s Law:</b> <code>P₁V₁ = P₂V₂</code></li>
            <li><b>Charles’ Law:</b> <code>V₁/T₁ = V₂/T₂</code></li>
            <li><b>Ideal Gas Law:</b> <code>PV = nRT</code></li>
            <li><b>STP:</b> 1 mol = 22.4 L at 273K, 1 atm</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Q:</b> Find the volume of 2 mol O₂ at 27°C, 2 atm. <b>A:</b> 24.6 L
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Stoichiometry & Yield -->
      <div class="chapter" id="stoich">
        <h2>Stoichiometry & Yield</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Step-by-Step</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li>Use mole ratios from balanced equations.</li>
            <li><b>Percent Yield:</b> <code>(actual/theoretical) × 100</code></li>
            <li><b>Limiting Reactant:</b> Smaller calculated product = limiting.</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Problem:</b> 10g H₂ + 80g O₂ → H₂O. What’s limiting? % yield if 70g H₂O formed?<br>
          <b>Answer:</b> O₂ limiting. % yield = 77.8%
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Periodic Trends & Table -->
      <div class="chapter" id="periodic">
        <h2>Periodic Trends & Table</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Trends & Practice</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li>Atomic radius ↓ left and down.</li>
            <li>Ionization energy, electronegativity ↑ up and right.</li>
            <li><b>Q:</b> Which has the highest ionization energy: Li, Be, B, or C? <b>A:</b> C</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Acids, Bases, Equilibrium -->
      <div class="chapter" id="acids">
        <h2>Acids, Bases, Equilibrium</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Formulas & Tips</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li><b>Acids:</b> H⁺ donors. <b>Bases:</b> H⁺ acceptors.</li>
            <li><b>pH = –log[H⁺]</b>; <b>pOH = –log[OH⁻]</b>; <b>pH + pOH = 14</b></li>
            <li><b>K_w = 1 × 10⁻¹⁴</b></li>
            <li><b>Equilibrium:</b> K = [products]/[reactants]</li>
            <li><b>Le Chatelier’s Principle:</b> System shifts to minimize stress</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Example:</b> If you increase [H₂] in N₂ + 3H₂ ⇌ 2NH₃, which way does equilibrium shift?<br>
          <b>Answer:</b> Right (toward NH₃).
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Colligative Properties -->
      <div class="chapter" id="colligative">
        <h2>Colligative Properties</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Essentials</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li>Boiling point elevation: <code>ΔT_b = iK_b m</code></li>
            <li>Freezing point depression: <code>ΔT_f = iK_f m</code></li>
            <li>i = # of particles; NaCl → 2, CaCl₂ → 3</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Challenge:</b> Which has the greatest freezing point depression: 1m NaCl, 1m glucose, 1m CaCl₂? <b>Answer:</b> 1m CaCl₂
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Redox & Oxidation -->
      <div class="chapter" id="redox">
        <h2>Redox & Oxidation Numbers</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Rules & Practice</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ul>
            <li>Oxidation = loss of e⁻; Reduction = gain of e⁻</li>
            <li>Elemental state = 0</li>
            <li>Oxygen = –2 (except peroxides)</li>
            <li>Hydrogen = +1 (–1 w/metals)</li>
          </ul>
          <b>Example:</b> Assign oxidation numbers in MnO₄⁻. <b>Answer:</b> Mn = +7, O = –2 each.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Comprehensive Review -->
      <div class="chapter" id="review">
        <h2>Comprehensive Review & Exam Practice</h2>
        <button class="collapsible">Hard Problems & Strategies</button>
        <div class="chapter-content">
          <ol>
            <li>
              <b>Stoichiometry Challenge:</b><br>
              A 10.0 g sample of CaCl₂ is added to 15.0 g Na₃PO₄. What mass of Ca₃(PO₄)₂ can be formed?
              <details><summary>Solution</summary>
                <div>
                  CaCl₂: 10/111 = 0.0901 mol<br>
                  Na₃PO₄: 15/164 = 0.0915 mol<br>
                  3:1 ratio, so CaCl₂ limits: 0.0901/3 = 0.0300 mol<br>
                  Ca₃(PO₄)₂: 0.0300 × 310 = <b>9.3 g</b>
                </div>
              </details>
            </li>
            <li>
              <b>Gas Law Application:</b><br>
              2.0 L of H₂ at 2 atm and 300K, what is the number of moles?
              <details><summary>Solution</summary>
                <div>
                  PV = nRT → n = PV/RT = (2×2)/(0.0821×300) ≈ 0.16 mol
                </div>
              </details>
            </li>
            <li>
              <b>Net Ionic Equation:</b>  
              Write the net ionic equation for: AgNO₃(aq) + NaCl(aq) → AgCl(s) + NaNO₃(aq)<br>
              <details><summary>Answer</summary>
                <div>Ag⁺(aq) + Cl⁻(aq) → AgCl(s)</div>
              </details>
            </li>
            <!-- Add more challenging review problems as you wish -->
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script>
    // Collapsible sections
    const coll = document.querySelectorAll(".collapsible");
    coll.forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener("click", function () {
        this.classList.toggle("active");
        let content = this.nextElementSibling;
        if (content.style.maxHeight) content.style.maxHeight = null;
        else content.style.maxHeight = content.scrollHeight + "px";
      });
    });

    // Simple search/filter function for quick lookup
    document.getElementById('searchInput').addEventListener('input', function () {
      const searchVal = this.value.toLowerCase();
      document.querySelectorAll('.chapter').forEach(chap => {
        if (chap.innerText.toLowerCase().includes(searchVal)) {
          chap.style.display = "";
        } else {
          chap.style.display = "none";
        }
      });
    });
  </script>
